# ================================
# Cursor Rules – uventorybiz
# ================================

# --- GENERAL BEHAVIOR ---
You are a senior full-stack engineer.
Prefer correctness, clarity, and maintainability over cleverness.
Do not hallucinate APIs, tables, or files that do not exist.
Ask before refactoring existing logic.

# --- PRODUCT ---
Product: uventorybiz — multi-tenant B2B business management (inventory + POS).
Clinical/patient/FHIR/telecare code lives under /purged and must not be re-wired without explicit instruction.

# --- TECH STACK ---
Backend: Node.js + TypeScript
Frontend: React + TypeScript
Styling: Tailwind CSS
Database: NeonDB (PostgreSQL)
Hosting: Railway
Email: Nodemailer (Gmail SMTP)

# --- ARCHITECTURE RULES ---
Business logic MUST NOT send emails directly.
All notifications must be event-driven (trigger-based).
All email sending must go through a centralized EmailService.
Notification logic must be isolated in a /notifications module.
Notifications are trigger-based: storage and cron call notificationTriggers/notificationService directly; there is no event bus. Add an event bus only if we need multiple subscribers or async decoupling.

# --- DATABASE RULES ---
Use PostgreSQL-compatible SQL.
Prefer UUID primary keys.
Always include:
- created_at
- updated_at

Do NOT modify existing tables unless explicitly instructed.
When adding tables:
- include proper foreign keys
- include indexes for lookup-heavy columns

# --- NOTIFICATION SYSTEM RULES ---
Notification types must be data-driven (DB-backed).
Recipients must be resolved from user_notification_preferences.
Never hardcode recipient emails.
Support per-user, per-notification enable/disable.

Notification sending flow:
Trigger (storage/cron) → notificationTriggers / notificationService → Channel handler → EmailService → Log result

Always log notification attempts in notification_logs.

# --- NOTIFICATION SCHEMA RULES ---
Do NOT model notification preferences using boolean columns
(e.g. email_enabled, sms_enabled, incident_alerts_enabled).

Notification preferences MUST be row-based:
- one row per (tenant, user, notification_type, channel)

Notification types MUST be data-driven and stored in a table.
Channels MUST be represented as data, not boolean flags.

The notifications table represents delivery/audit only.
It must NOT store rules or preferences.

Design must allow adding:
- new notification types
- new channels (e.g. sms, WhatsApp)
WITHOUT schema migrations.

# --- EVENT HANDLING ---
Current design: trigger-based (no event bus). Storage and cron call notificationTriggers/notificationService directly.
If an event bus is added later: use a lightweight EventEmitter or equivalent; events in SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE; payloads serializable JSON.

# --- EMAIL RULES ---
Reuse existing Nodemailer configuration.
Do NOT inline email templates.
Templates must support variables.
Avoid sensitive data in email bodies.

# --- FRONTEND RULES ---
Admin notification settings must:
- Be accessible only to company admins
- Use existing API patterns
- Be clean, minimal, and scalable
- Avoid deeply nested state

Prefer controlled components.
Prefer server-driven configuration.

# --- API RULES ---
All admin endpoints must:
- Be authenticated
- Be company-scoped
- Validate input
- Return predictable JSON responses

Use REST-style routes.
Do not introduce GraphQL.

# --- TYPESCRIPT RULES ---
Do not use `any` unless explicitly allowed.
Prefer enums or string unions for notification types.
Share types between frontend and backend where possible.

# --- SCALABILITY ---
Design so SMS, in-app, or push notifications can be added later.
Channels must be pluggable.
Avoid logic that assumes email-only.

# --- SAFETY & RELIABILITY ---
Never block HTTP requests while sending emails.
Avoid unbounded loops.
Add basic error handling and logging.

# --- CODING STYLE ---
Prefer small, composable functions.
Avoid massive files.
Add comments where future extensions are expected.

# --- WHAT NOT TO DO ---
❌ Do NOT send emails inside controllers
❌ Do NOT hardcode notification recipients
❌ Do NOT bypass user preferences
❌ Do NOT break existing auth-related emails
❌ Do NOT refactor unrelated systems

# --- DEFAULT ASSUMPTIONS ---
If unclear:
- Ask before implementing
- Prefer minimal viable implementation
- Follow existing project patterns
